<sections.3>
Discussion
arly-onset cardiomyopathies are severe diseases. he ational ustralian hildhood ardiomyopathy tudy roup recently published survival rates for pediatric . reedom from death or transplantation was reduced to 72% 1 year after presentation and to 63% at 5 years [7]. t appears imperative to make all efforts to improve the prognosis of such children. dentification of causative genetic defects can help in several ways. irst, it allows separation of family members at risk from those who need not be closely monitored. lose monitoring of individuals at risk can help initiate treatment of both, heart failure and arrhythmias at an early point of the disease course. econd, it offers opportunities for prenatal diagnosis. hird, the identification of disease-causing mutations enables acquiring a deeper understanding of the underlying pathophysiology in this devastating condition.
everal pathways for cardiac diseases have already been identified using this approach. utations in ion channel genes were identified in familial arrhythmias such as long- and rugada syndromes [9]. berrations in sarcomeric genes can lead to hypertrophic cardiomyopathy [2]. isruption of desmosomal function is the unifying pathomechanism in  [8]. or , the picture is less clear. part from a high proportion of non-genetic forms, even familial  shows a high degree of genetic heterogeneity, with different subcellular systems being involved in the disease-causing process [16].
s the index patient had been diagnosed with  due to the strong left ventricular dysfunction, we would not have had a realistic chance to identify the underlying genetic defect in the family described, if there had been no additional phenotypes. he characteristic combination of biventricular cardiomyopathy, woolly hair and palmoplantar keratoderma known as arvajal syndrome led us to assume that mutations in  could be the problem in this family. inally, we identified a homozygous 2 bp deletion in this gene leading to a premature chain-termination mutation. t the age of 10, 5 years after the initial diagnosis, the index patient was transplanted. e was diagnosed with  involvement, and at the time of explantation the heart showed severe biventricular involvement. ccording to findings by en-howdhry et al., [17] who identified three distinct patterns of disease expression, the phenotype of the index patient allows grouping the genotype into the left-dominant disease expression pattern. he phenotypic differences observed between the index patient and the homozygous younger sister, however, could be accounted to her young age, since both the index patient and the deceased brother were free of cardiac involvement until the ages of 4 and 5 years.
 is a major constituent of the desmosome. ike several other desmosomal genes,  belongs to disease genes that cause . n addition,  is highly expressed in epithelia where desmosomes are important for mechanical integrity. t is therefore not surprising that, apart from cardiac alterations, mutations in  can also lead to skin phenotypes and hair abnormalities. ven isolated cutaneous phenotypes without cardiac disease can be caused by  mutations, i.e., striate palmoplantar keratoderma, skin-fragility/woolly hair syndrome and lethal acantholytic epidermolysis bullosa (). issense, nonsense and truncating frameshift mutations have been identified in these cases (ig. 6) [1, 5, 9, 11]. ven though an obvious phenotypeβ€“genotype correlation regarding  mutations has not yet been drawn, it is tempting to speculate that truncations/modifications affecting the -terminal domain of -1 predispose to cardiomyopathy due to present and previous studies.
or the specific syndromic phenotype of arvajal syndrome, only three mutations have been described so far. wo exhibit a recessive trait. he homozygous deletion c.7901del. G (p.K2542fsX2559) truncates DSP at the C-terminus [11], affecting both isoforms. A homozygous nonsense mutation (p.R1267X) in the DSP-1 specific region of exon 23 leads to shortening of the rod domain exclusively in DSP-1 [18]. Dominant mutations seem capable of producing similar phenotypes [3, 4, 12, 15]. The frameshift mutation G1737fsX1742 described here is situated in the DSP-1 specific region of exon 23, similar to the p.R1267X mutation. Since both alleles are affected, the truncation leads to complete loss of intact full-length DSP-1. Instead, only the truncated isoform was detectable in skin biopsies of this patient. Since DSP-2 is only expressed at very low levels in cardiac muscle and the fact that we found orthotopic DSP expression on immunohistopathology using an antibody recognizing the truncated part of DSP, we conclude that the truncated isoform was still incorporated into the desmosomes but lacked functional integrity eventually leading to the early onset of heart failure in the affected individual.
